This project documents the process of configuring, troubleshooting, and securing SSH access on a GL.iNet GL-MT300N-V2 (OpenWRT-based) router using a Windows OpenSSH client.

It includes real-world debugging of SSH authentication issues, key setup, and Dropbear configuration.

---

## Project Goal

The goal of this lab was to:
- Establish SSH access to a GL.iNet router from Windows
- Resolve authentication and compatibility issues
- Configure SSH key-based authentication
- Understand Dropbear (OpenWRT SSH server) behavior
- Practice real-world network troubleshooting and hardening

---

## Environment

- Router: GL.iNet GL-MT300N-V2 (OpenWRT / Dropbear)
- Client OS: Windows 10/11
- SSH Client: OpenSSH (Windows built-in)
- Key Type: ed25519
- Network: Local LAN (192.168.8.1)

---

## Key Steps Completed

### 1. Initial SSH Access
Connected to router via:
```bash
ssh root@192.168.8.1

Encountered SSH host key compatibility issue requiring legacy support for ssh-rsa.

2. Host Key Compatibility Fix
Resolved using:
ssh -o HostKeyAlgorithms=+ssh-rsa -o PubkeyAcceptedAlgorithms=+ssh-rsa root@192.168.8.1

3. SSH Key Generation (Windows)
Generated ed25519 key pair:

ssh-keygen -t ed25519

Public key location:

C:\Users\<User>\.ssh\id_ed25519.pub

4. Manual Key Deployment to Router
Created SSH directory and authorized keys file:

mkdir -p ~/.ssh
chmod 700 ~/.ssh

cat > ~/.ssh/authorized_keys

Pasted public key and saved with:

CTRL + D

Set permissions:

chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys

5. Dropbear Configuration Review
Verified SSH settings:

cat /etc/config/dropbear

Key settings:

Password authentication enabled
Root login enabled
Port: 22
